  "url": "sec-indices-and-logarithms.html#subsubsec-logarithms-notation-20",
  "type": "Checkpoint",
  "number": "1.2.35",
  "title": "Rewrite Complex Exponential Relationship into Logarithmic Form.",
  "body": " Rewrite Complex Exponential Relationship into Logarithmic Form   Load the question by clicking the button below.       Rewrite a complex exponential relationship into logarithmic form    <p>During a simulation, a machine amplifies a signal using exponential growth. After several cycles, the signal reaches a strength of \\({@number@}\\), generated using base \\({@base@}\\).<\/p> <p>Write the logarithmic form of the statement:<\/p> <p>\\[ {@base@}^{@chosen_exp@} = {@number@} \\]<\/p> <p>Express your answer in the form \\(\\log_{a}(b)\\).<\/p> <p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]<\/p>    <h3>Worked Solution<\/h3> <p>The exponential relationship is:<\/p> <p>\\[ {@base@}^{@chosen_exp@} = {@number@}. \\]<\/p> <p>We use the identity:<\/p> <p>\\[ a^k = N \\quad \\Longleftrightarrow \\quad \\log_a(N) = k. \\]<\/p> <p>So:<\/p> <p>\\[ \\log_{ {@base@} }({@number@}) = {@chosen_exp@}. \\]<\/p> <p>This is written as:<\/p> <p>\\[ \\frac{\\log({@number@})}{\\log({@base@})}. \\]<\/p>   2  0.1  0    2025073100    \/* Choose a base that produces larger results *\/ base: rand([2,3,4,5,10]); \/* Two exponents to choose from *\/ exp1: rand([3,4,5,6]); exp2: exp1 + rand([1,2,3]); \/* slightly larger exponent *\/ \/* Choose between exp1 and exp2 to create variation *\/ chosen_exp: rand([exp1, exp2]); \/* Compute number *\/ number: base^chosen_exp; \/* Correct logarithm form using Maxima syntax *\/ log_expr: log(number)\/log(base); \/* Common mistakes *\/ m1: log(chosen_exp)\/log(base); \/* swaps result with exponent *\/ m2: log(base)\/log(number); \/* reverses arguments *\/ m3: number\/chosen_exp; \/* arithmetic misuse *\/       <p>{@base@}^{@chosen_exp@} = {@number@}<\/p>    <p id=\"author\">Michael Onyimbo<\/p> <p id=\"concept\"><\/p> <p id=\"reviewer\"><\/p> <p id=\"reviewer\"><\/p> <p id=\"description\"> The question requires the learner to convert a more complex exponential statement into logarithmic form by identifying the correct base and result while applying the definition of logarithms.<\/p>   1  0  0   <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:green;\"><i class=\"fa fa-check\"><\/i><\/span> Correct answer, well done.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:orange;\"><i class=\"fa fa-adjust\"><\/i><\/span> Your answer is partially correct.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:red;\"><i class=\"fa fa-times\"><\/i><\/span> Incorrect answer.   .  *10  none  1  i  cos-1  lang  [  0    ans1  algebraic  log(number)\/log(base)  15  1  0   0    1  0  0  1  3     prt1  1.0000000  1  1      0   AlgEquiv  ans1  log(number)\/log(base)   0  =  1   -1  prt1-1-T     =  0   -1  prt1-1-F       1627317658  84405787  513313332  886951485  1070035133  1668976912  1646856099  879192544  2134883010  1959452724  1203624073  122874616  1180422593  43916218  1451919885  600639619  397751899  1331294408  1939895846  85965175   1  Test case assuming the teacher's input gets full marks.   ans1  log(number)\/log(base)    prt1  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt1-1-T       "
