  "body": " Circumference of a Circle Under Enlargement   Load the question by clicking the button below.       Circumference of a circle under enlargement    <p>The radius of a circle is <strong>{@r0@} cm<\/strong>. The circle is enlarged by a scale factor of <strong>{@k@}<\/strong>. Find the circumference of the image of the circle after the enlargement.<\/p><p>[[input:ans1]] cm[[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]<\/p>    <h3>Worked solution<\/h3> <p> The original radius is \\( r = {@r0@} \\) cm. <\/p> <p> After enlargement by a scale factor of \\( {@k@} \\), the new radius is<\/p> <p> \\( r' = {@k@} \\times {@r0@} = {@r1@} \\) cm. <\/p> <p> The circumference of a circle is given by \\( C = 2\\pi r. \\) <\/p> <p> So the circumference of the enlarged circle is<\/p> <p> \\( C = 2\\times \\frac{22}{7} \\times {@r1@} = {@C1@} \\) cm. <\/p> <p> Equivalently, since circumference scales linearly,<\/p><p> \\( C = {@k@} \\times (2\\times \\frac{22}{7} \\times {@r0@}) = {@ta@} \\) cm. <\/p>   1  0.1  0    2025073100    \/* Original radius (in cm): decimal, nice values *\/ r0 : rand_with_step(0.7,28,0.7); \/* values from 2.0 to 5.0 in steps of 0.5 *\/ \/* Scale factor *\/ k : rand([0.25,0.5,0.75,1.5,2]); \/* values from 1.25 to 2.5 *\/ \/* New radius after enlargement *\/ r1 : k * r0; \/* Circumference after enlargement *\/ C1 : 2 * 22\/7 * r1; ta:C1; \/*mistakes*\/ \/*Forgetting to apply the scale factor*\/ ta1:2 * 22\/7 * r0; \/*Confusion between radius and diameter*\/ ta2:2 *2* 22\/7 * r1;       <p>Circumference of the image = {@ta@} <\/p>      1  0  0   <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:green;\"><i class=\"fa fa-check\"><\/i><\/span> Correct answer, well done.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:orange;\"><i class=\"fa fa-adjust\"><\/i><\/span> Your answer is partially correct.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:red;\"><i class=\"fa fa-times\"><\/i><\/span> Incorrect answer.   .  *10  none  1  i  cos-1  lang  [  0    ans1  algebraic  ta  5  1  0   0    0  0  0  1  3     prt1  1.0000000  1  1      0   NumAbsolute  ans1  ta  0.00000000001  0  =  1   -1  prt1-1-T     =  0   1  prt1-1-F       1  Forgetting to apply the scale factor  NumAbsolute  ans1  ta1  0.0000001  0  +  0   -1  prt1-2-T   <p> It looks like you may have calculated the circumference using the original radius of the circle. Remember, when a shape is enlarged, all lengths are multiplied by the scale factor. This means the radius must first be scaled before finding the circumference. Make sure you apply the scale factor to the radius before using the circumference formula. <\/p>   -  0   2  prt1-2-F       2  Confusion between radius and diameter  NumAbsolute  ans1  ta2  0.0000001  0  +  0   -1  prt1-3-T   <p> It looks like you might have confused the radius and the diameter of the circle. Remember, the formula for the circumference is \\( C = 2\\pi r \\), which uses the radius, not the diameter. The diameter is twice the radius, so using it directly in the formula will give an incorrect result. Make sure you are using the correct measurement before applying the circumference formula. <\/p>   -  0   -1  prt1-3-F       1399585896  969058654  1922801440  884293813  1672502579  1286395488  1227985350  1697200459  821221419  625246398  1952321018  1183038094  1536276755  1205794151  1946980738  249948234  1343577732  1398766038  2105394752  546484390   1  Test case assuming the teacher's input gets full marks.   ans1  ta    prt1  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt1-1-T     2  Forgetting to apply the scale factor   ans1  ta1    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-2-T     3  Confusion between radius and diameter   ans1  ta2    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-3-T       "
