  "url": "sec-section-similarity-and-enlargement.html#subsubsec-volume-scale-factor-9",
  "type": "Checkpoint",
  "number": "2.1.43",
  "title": "Finding the Capacity of a Larger Container.",
  "body": " Finding the Capacity of a Larger Container   Load the question by clicking the button below.       Finding the Capacity of a Larger Container Using Similarity    <p>Two similar containers have heights of {@a@} cm and {@b@} cm respectively. If the smaller container holds {@c@} ml, what is the capacity of the larger container? <b>Note:<\/b> Write your answer correct to <b>2<\/b> decimal places.<\/p> <p>[[input:ans1]] ml[[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]<\/p>    <h3>Worked solution<\/h3> <p>Given the linear scale factor (L.S.F)= \\(\\frac{{@b@}}{{@a@}}\\)<\/p> <p>Volume scale factor (V.S.F) = \\((L.S.F)^3 = (\\frac{{@b@}}{{@a@}})^3 = {@k^3@}\\)<\/p> <p>Given the capacity of the small container as {@c@} ml, then the capacity of larger container is given by;<\/p> <p>\\(\\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\quad \\frac{{@b1@}}{{@a1@}}= \\frac{x}{{@c@}} \\Rightarrow x = \\frac{{@c@}\\times {@b1@}}{{@a1@}} = {@larger_container@}={@ta@}\\) ml<\/p>   1  0.1  0    2025073100    \/* Side lengths of similar regular polygons *\/ a : rand(9) + 3; \/* side length of smaller polygon *\/ b : a + rand(9) + 1; \/* side length of larger polygon, ensure b > a *\/ \/* volume of the smaller container *\/ c : rand_with_step(25,300,5) ; \/* Scale factor between corresponding sides *\/ k : b \/ a; \/*cubic scale*\/ b1:b^3; a1:a^3; \/* volume of the larger container (area scales with square of side ratio) *\/ larger_container : c * k^3; ta:decimalplaces( larger_container,2); \/*mistakes*\/ ta1:k*c; ta2:decimalplaces((1\/k^3)*c,2); ta3:c * k^2;       <p>volume of the smaller container={@c@}<\/p> <p>volume of the larger container={@ta@}<\/p>      1  0  0   <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:green;\"><i class=\"fa fa-check\"><\/i><\/span> Correct answer, well done.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:orange;\"><i class=\"fa fa-adjust\"><\/i><\/span> Your answer is partially correct.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:red;\"><i class=\"fa fa-times\"><\/i><\/span> Incorrect answer.   .  *10  none  1  i  cos-1  lang  [  0    ans1  algebraic  ta  5  1  0   0    0  0  0  1  3     prt1  1.0000000  1  1      0   NumAbsolute  ans1  ta  0.01  0  =  1   -1  prt1-1-T     =  0   1  prt1-1-F       1  Using the length scale factor directly  AlgEquiv  ans1  ta1   0  +  0   -1  prt1-2-T   <p> It looks like you may have used the scale factor for lengths directly to find the new capacity. Remember, when containers are similar, lengths scale by the scale factor, but <strong>volumes<\/strong> scale by the <strong>cube<\/strong> of the scale factor. Make sure you cube the ratio of the corresponding heights before multiplying it by the original volume. <\/p>   -  0   2  prt1-2-F       2  Inverting the scale factor  AlgEquiv  ans1  ta2   0  +  0   -1  prt1-3-T   <p> It appears that you may have used the ratio of the larger height to the smaller height in the wrong order. When scaling up from the smaller container to the larger one. Check the direction of scaling before calculating the volume. <\/p>   -  0   3  prt1-3-F       3  Squaring the scale facto  AlgEquiv  ans1  ta3   0  +  0   -1  prt1-4-T   <p> It seems like you squared the ratio of the heights when finding the capacity.Squaring the scale factor gives the ratio of <strong>areas<\/strong>, not volumes. Since capacity depends on volume, you must use the <strong>cube<\/strong> of the scale factor instead. <\/p>   -  0   -1  prt1-4-F       1888312194  1797272023  452151587  297282071  642147960  1387687611  1083938283  1583672595  158736662  1537002686  1486635612  142836434  1258156807  1348420741  384916768  968167599  2024802024  1893331229  1994180150  6799222   1  Test case assuming the teacher's input gets full marks.   ans1  ta    prt1  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt1-1-T     2  Using the length scale factor directly   ans1  ta1    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-2-T     3  Inverting the scale factor   ans1  ta2    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-3-T     4  Squaring the scale factor   ans1  ta3    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-4-T       "
