  "id": "subsubsec-volume-scale-factor-10",
  "level": "2",
  "url": "sec-section-similarity-and-enlargement.html#subsubsec-volume-scale-factor-10",
  "type": "Checkpoint",
  "number": "2.1.45",
  "title": "Finding the Height of a Larger Can.",
  "body": " Finding the Height of a Larger Can   Load the question by clicking the button below.       Finding the Height of a Larger Can from Volume Ratio    <p>Two similar cans have volumes of {@volume_list_a@} \\(\\text{m}^3\\) and {@volume_list_b@} \\(\\text{m}^3\\)respectively. If the smaller can has a height of {@c@} \\(\\text{m}\\), what is the height of the larger can?<\/p><p>[[input:ans1]] m[[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]<\/p>    <h3>Worked solution<\/h3> <p>Since the two cans are <strong>similar solids<\/strong>, the ratio of their corresponding linear dimensions is equal to the <strong>cube root of the ratio of their volumes<\/strong>.<\/p> <p>\\(\\frac{H_{\\text{large}}}{H_{\\text{small}}} = \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{V_{\\text{large}}}{V_{\\text{small}}}} \\) <\/p> <p> Substituting the given values: \\( \\frac{H_{\\text{large}}}{{@c@}} = \\sqrt[3]{\\frac{{@volume_list_b@}}{{@volume_list_a@}}} = {@cuberoot@} \\) <\/p> <p> Hence, the height of the larger can is: \\( H_{\\text{large}} = {@cuberoot@} \\times {@c@} = {@height@}\\,\\text{m} \\) <\/p> <p> Rounding to two decimal places, the final answer is: \\( \\boxed{{@ta@}\\,\\text{m}} \\) <\/p>   1  0.1  0    2025073100    \/* Generate perfect-volume values for a and b *\/ volume_list_a:rand ([8,27,64,125,216,343,512]); \/* extend if desired *\/ volume_list_b:rand ([729,1000,1331,1728,2197]); \/* extend if desired *\/ \/* height of the smaller can *\/ c: rand(16) + 7; \/*cube root of b\/a*\/ cuberoot:(volume_list_b\/volume_list_a)^(1\/3); \/* height of the cone*\/ height:float(cuberoot*c); ta:decimalplaces(height,2); \/*mistakes*\/ \/*Using the volume ratio directly as the height ratio*\/ ta1:decimalplaces((volume_list_b\/volume_list_a)*c,2);       <p>Height of the larger can = {@ta@}<\/p>      1  0  0   <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:green;\"><i class=\"fa fa-check\"><\/i><\/span> Correct answer, well done.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:orange;\"><i class=\"fa fa-adjust\"><\/i><\/span> Your answer is partially correct.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:red;\"><i class=\"fa fa-times\"><\/i><\/span> Incorrect answer.   .  *10  none  1  i  cos-1  lang  [  0    ans1  algebraic  ta  5  1  0   0    0  0  0  1  3     prt1  1.0000000  1  1      0   AlgEquiv  ans1  ta   0  =  1   -1  prt1-1-T     =  0   1  prt1-1-F       1  Using the volume ratio directly as the height ratio  AlgEquiv  ans1  ta1   0  +  0   -1  prt1-2-T   <p> It looks like you may have used the ratio of the volumes directly to find the new height. Remember, when solids are similar, volumes scale with the <strong>cube<\/strong> of the linear scale factor. To find the ratio of the heights, you must take the <strong>cube root<\/strong> of the ratio of the volumes. <\/p>   -  0   -1  prt1-2-F       2029999784  713192678  1673125481  1367168093  986716178  940502346  1901669421  1704001595  624592332  1387724132  569275624  1005492784  909616491  400365834  2040091319  1911112448  1014923249  128635935  754649357  719575431   1  Test case assuming the teacher's input gets full marks.   ans1  ta    prt1  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt1-1-T       "
