  "id": "subsubsec-volume-scale-factor-11",
  "level": "2",
  "url": "sec-section-similarity-and-enlargement.html#subsubsec-volume-scale-factor-11",
  "type": "Checkpoint",
  "number": "2.1.47",
  "title": "Ratio of Volumes of Similar Solids.",
  "body": " Ratio of Volumes of Similar Solids   Load the question by clicking the button below.       Ratio of volumes of similar solids    <p>The corresponding sides of two <strong>similar<\/strong> blocks of wood measure {@a@} cm and {@b@} cm. Find the ratio of their volumes.<\/p><p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]<\/p>    <h3>Worked solution<\/h3> <p> Since the blocks are <strong>similar<\/strong>, all corresponding lengths scale by the same factor. <\/p> <p> The linear scale factor is: \\[ \\frac{@b@}{@a@} \\] <\/p> <p> For similar solids, volumes scale with the <strong>cube<\/strong> of the linear scale factor: \\[ \\left({@scale@}\\right)^3 = {@ta@}. \\] <\/p> <p> Therefore, the ratio of the volumes of the smaller block to the larger block is: \\[ 1 : {@ta@} = {@ta@}. \\] <\/p>   1  0.1  0    2025073100    \/* Randomly generate two corresponding side lengths *\/ a: rand(8) + 3; \/* gives a between 3 and 10 *\/ k: rand(4) + 2; \/* scale factor between 2 and 5 *\/ b: a * k; g : gcd(a,b); if g > 1 then b:a+1 else b:a; \/* Linear scale factor *\/ scale: b \/ a; \/* Correct ratio of volumes *\/ ta: (scale)^3; ta1:(1\/scale)^3; \/*mistakes*\/ ta2:scale; ta3:a\/b;       <p>Ratio of the volumes = {@ta@} or {@ta1@}. <\/p>      1  0  0   <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:green;\"><i class=\"fa fa-check\"><\/i><\/span> Correct answer, well done.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:orange;\"><i class=\"fa fa-adjust\"><\/i><\/span> Your answer is partially correct.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:red;\"><i class=\"fa fa-times\"><\/i><\/span> Incorrect answer.   .  *10  none  1  i  cos-1  lang  [  0    ans1  algebraic  ta  5  1  0   0    1  0  0  1  3     prt1  1.0000000  1  1   correst_ans : if (ans1 = ta or ans1 = ta1) then 1 else 0; mistake_1 : if (ans1 = ta2 or ans1 = ta3) then 1 else 0;    0   AlgEquiv  correst_ans  1   0  =  1   -1  prt1-1-T     =  0   1  prt1-1-F       1  Using the length ratio directly  AlgEquiv  mistake_1  1   0  +  0   -1  prt1-2-T   <p> It seems like you used the ratio of the corresponding sides only. You treated the scale factor {@a@} cm to {@b@} cm as if it applied directly to the volumes. Remember that for similar solids, volumes scale with the <strong>cube<\/strong> of the linear scale factor. <\/p>   -  0   -1  prt1-2-F       1458668106  2043399042  1743429665  1322784655  196547418  2106727249   1  Test case assuming the teacher's input gets full marks.   ans1  ta    prt1  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt1-1-T     2  Using the length ratio directly   ans1  ta2    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-2-T     3  Using the length ratio directly   ans1  ta3    prt1  0.0000000   prt1-2-T       "
