  "title": "Finding Sines and Cosines of Complementary Angles.",
  "body": " Finding Sines and Cosines of Complementary Angles   Load the question by clicking the button below.       Finding Sines and Cosines of Complementary Angles    <p> Find the acute angles \\(\\alpha\\) and \\(\\beta\\) that satisfy each of the following trigonometric equations: <\/p> <ol type=\"a\"> <li><p>\\(\\cos\\, 45^\\circ = \\sin \\alpha\\)<\/p> <p>\\(\\alpha=\\)[[input:ans1]]\\(^\\circ\\)[[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]<\/p> <\/li> <li><p>\\(\\cos\\, \\beta = \\sin 5\\beta\\)<\/p> <p>\\(\\beta =\\)[[input:ans2]]\\(^\\circ\\)[[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]<\/p> <\/li> <li><p>\\(\\sin\\,2\\alpha = \\cos 30^\\circ\\)<\/p> <p>\\(\\alpha=\\)[[input:ans3]]\\(^\\circ\\)[[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]<\/p> <\/li> <\/ol> <p>    <p> <ol type='a'> <li> <p>\\(\\cos\\, 45^\\circ = \\sin \\alpha\\)<\/p> <p>Implies that,<br> \\( \\begin{align} {@theta_1@}^\\circ + \\alpha &=90^\\circ \\\\ \\alpha &= 90^\\circ-{@theta_1@}^\\circ \\\\ &={@sol1@}^\\circ \\end{align} \\) <br> Therefore, <br> The acute angle \\(\\alpha = {@sol1@}^\\circ\\) <\/p> <\/li> <li> <p>\\(\\cos\\, \\beta = \\sin 5\\beta\\)<\/p> <p>Implies that,<br> \\( \\begin{align} \\beta+ {@num_1@}\\beta &=90^\\circ \\\\ {@sol@}\\beta &= 90^\\circ \\\\ \\beta &= \\frac{90^\\circ}{{@sol@}}\\\\ &={@sol2@}^\\circ \\end{align} \\) <br> Therefore, <br> The acute angle \\(\\beta = {@sol2@}^\\circ\\) <\/p> <\/li> <li> <p>\\(\\sin\\,2\\alpha = \\cos 30^\\circ\\)<\/p> <p>Implies that,<br> \\( \\begin{align} 2 \\alpha + {@theta_2@}^\\circ &=90^\\circ \\\\ 2 \\alpha &= 90^\\circ - {@theta_2@}^\\circ\\\\ \\alpha &= \\frac{{@sol_2@}^\\circ}{2}\\\\ &={@sol3@}^\\circ \\end{align} \\) <br> Therefore, <br> The acute angle \\(\\beta = {@sol3@}^\\circ\\) <\/p> <\/li> <\/ol> <\/p>   15  0.1  0    2025073100    theta_1:rand_with_step(10,90,5); \/*Randomizing degrees of part a*\/ theta_2:rand_with_step(10,90,10);\/*Randomizing degrees of part c*\/ num_1:rand_with_step(2,20,2); \/*Solution*\/ \/* (a) Solution *\/ sol1: 90-theta_1; \/* (b) Solution *\/ sol:num_1+1; sol2:90\/(num_1+1); \/* (c) Solution *\/ sol_2:90-theta_2; sol3:(90-theta_2)\/2;       <p>Part (a) of the question<\/p> <p>\\(\\text{The acute angle}\\, \\alpha={@sol1@}^\\circ\\)<\/p> <p>Part (b) of the question<\/p> <p>\\(\\text{The acute angle}\\, \\beta={@sol2@}^\\circ\\)<\/p> <p>Part (c) of the question<\/p> <p>\\(\\text{The acute angle}\\, \\alpha={@sol3@}^\\circ\\)<\/p>      1  0  0   <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:green;\"><i class=\"fa fa-check\"><\/i><\/span> Correct answer, well done.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:orange;\"><i class=\"fa fa-adjust\"><\/i><\/span> Your answer is partially correct.    <span style=\"font-size: 1.5em; color:red;\"><i class=\"fa fa-times\"><\/i><\/span> Incorrect answer.   .  *10  none  1  i  cos-1  lang  [  0    ans1  algebraic  sol1  7  1  0   0    1  0  0  1  3     ans2  algebraic  sol2  7  1  0   0    1  0  0  1  3     ans3  algebraic  sol3  7  1  0   0    1  0  0  1  3     prt1  1.0000000  1  1      0  Checks for the correctalpha  AlgEquiv  ans1  sol1   0  =  1   -1  prt1-1-T     =  0   -1  prt1-1-F        prt2  1.0000000  1  1      0  Checks for the correct beta  AlgEquiv  ans2  sol2   0  =  1   -1  prt2-1-T     =  0   -1  prt2-1-F        prt3  1.0000000  1  1      0  Checks for the correct beta  AlgEquiv  ans3  sol3   0  =  1   -1  prt3-1-T     =  0   -1  prt3-1-F       1498791632  933751405  1168044800  1317545600  1211450507  977152072  1363826559  1037945741  524532633  1067551243   1  Test case assuming the teacher's input gets full marks.   ans1  sol1    ans2  sol2    ans3  sol3    prt1  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt1-1-T    prt2  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt2-1-T    prt3  1.0000000  0.0000000  prt3-1-T       "
